column2: Wesley House Community Center’s expanding childcare and addressing food insecurity
column23: The funding through City of Knoxville ARPA funds allowed Wesley House to continue affordable and high quality programming. Our community bases its use of resources of word of mouth referral, which has always been our agency's largest tool for serving our community. Because of this funding, Wesley House was able to provide programming in a safe and healthy manner. Once we had this reputation, our program participants were able to tell their peers, which kept our childcare program full and food pantry busy. Our current retention rate for our childcare program is 96% from summer camp to after school programming.

column23: The funds helped make it possible for children age birth - 5 to be cared for so that mothers could continue their substance abuse counseling and life skills classes. Children also received mental health services in the form of Child/Parent Psychotherapy. Staff were retained in order to care for children and to provide mental health therapy for mothers, and allowed Susannah's House to attract more clients.

Fighting to Save Lives thru the Mental, Physical and Emotional Training Disciplines of Martial Arts

column23:
Staff details: 
 * Our total staff went from 33 in 1/2023 to 41 in 7/2023.
 * Of our staff as of 1/28/23, we only lost 4 staff members. Mainly reasons out of LOA's control. (moving, leaving childcare altogether)
 * This grant has supported 8 new jobs. 
New hires: 
 * We hired 24 new staff members from 2/10/23 to 7/28/23.
 * 19 of the 24 new hires were possible in the first 3 months of offering the new base wages.
 * Of the 24 new hires, about 8 were let go prior to their 90 days for not being good fits for LOA. Another 8 also left for various reasons of moving or not wanting to be in childcare anymore. While the percentage of staff that left if high for many companies, this is a great improvement for many childcare centers. Getting quality candidate has been incredible difficult since the COVID pandemic so this is progress that a childcare center can be more selective on staff members.
 * LOA retention has grown our new staff and 7-12 months staff members while maintaining our greater than 1 year staff members.     1/26/23: 0-6 months: 16 staff members, 7-12 months: 3 staff members, 1yr1mo-2yr: 8 staff members, 2yr1mo-3yr: 3 staff members, >3yr: 3 staff members 
    7/28/23: 0-6 months: 19 staff members, 7-12 months: 9 staff members, 1yr1mo-2yr: 6 staff members, 2yr1mo-3yr: 4 staff members, >3yr: 3 staff members

Staff responses: 
 * Our staff was incredibly thankful for increase in wages and to be fully staffed.
 * Being fully staffed is helping give them time for lesson planning and planning for student enrichment activities to meet our mission statement.
 * Improved efficiency and efficacy in onboarding staff.

column2: Thrive Afterschool and Summer Program Providing Nutritious Meals and Academic Support
column23: The funds provided through United Way attracted and retained at-risk students that we were able to serve by providing nutritious meals and snacks daily. Our program provides a vital resource to an underserved neighborhood where 49% of the students we serve worry their food will run out and there won't be money to purchase more food. We have a waitlist at most locations for students interested in joining our program and one of the main reasons they are seeking to join is for the access to nutrient-rich food.

* Increased Enrollment: The no-cost tuition for the Academic Center makes it more accessible to a broader range of families, potentially increasing enrollment. Families who might have been deterred by tuition costs are more likely to enroll their children.  
 * Improved Mental Health for Students: Providing free mental health services can positively impact the mental well-being of students. When parents see these services are available, they may be more inclined to keep their children in the program, leading to higher retention rates.

column2: Tuition Assistance for low-income/at risk families
column23: Our lower income families were ale to have a tuition break for multiple weeks of childcare from the receipt of these funds. Families were able to take what would have gone on the cost of childcare and use those funds on other expenditures knowing that their childcare balance was taken care of for a few weeks. Some families who had gotten behind on their childcare bills were able to catch up and still have some left over fund in their accounts for future childcare weeks.
